        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 176,
      "author": {
        "id": 1002080
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-10-15T19:42:02Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I think the jury is out on which one is cheaper, but I think for structs with little data (in this case it\u0027s 3 strings, which means 3 pointer) it\u0027s better to pass by value, because otherwise you have to do a nil check\n\nfunc (uo *userOptions) formatHTML() bool {\n  if uo \u003d\u003d nil {\n    return false\n  }\n  return ...\n}\n\nAlso according to the Go FAQ: https://golang.org/doc/faq#methods_on_values_or_pointers\n\"For types such as basic types, slices, and small structs, a value receiver is very cheap so unless the semantics of the method requires a pointer, a value receiver is efficient and clear.\"\n\nisHTML() is a better name, I\u0027ll use that.",
      "parentUuid": "57c43d24_6a2a88ea",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 176,
        "startChar": 9,
        "endLine": 176,
